Before analysing the data

  • Individual dataframes joined
  • Splitting cells containing multiple variables
  • Converting strings to numbers
  • Grouping numerical varibales in intervals
  • Ensuring that all variables are correctly classified

Identifying and visualising trends with ggplot

Approach

  • A large number of plots were generated quickly to more efficiently identify interesting trends
  • For this purpose the same plot was stratified on different factor columns, and in addition pivot_longer() and facet_wrap() was used

Tumor size and cause of death

  • Prostate cancer showed the second largest tumor size
  • Other than prostate cancer, all other causes of death showed difference in stage leads to difference in the tumor size Repo (plot #8)

Prostatic acid phosphatase and cause of death

  • PA phosphatase levels are increased in patients with bone metastases
  • PA phosphatase levels are highest in patients that die from prostate cancer

Repo (plot #1)

Tumor size and bone metastases

  • Tumors are larger in patients that have died from prostate cancer
  • Tumors are larger in patients with metastases

Repo (plot #5)

Status and bone metastases

  • Risk of dying from prostate cancer doubles if the cancer spreads from the prostate

Repo (plot #2)

Serum hemoglobin and bone metastases

  • Serum hemoglobin levels are higher in patients without metastases
  • Serum hemoglobin levels drop with increased age

Repo (plot #4)

Activity and bone metastases

  • The activity level is affected by disease progress
  • Bone metastases leads to reduced activity

Repo (plot #3)

Estrogen dose and status

  • Estrogen is important for survival if the cancer has spread
  • High estrogen dose has a negetive effect as age increase

Repo (plot #6 and #7)

Predictive models and ANN

Linear regression of blood pressure

  • The only linear regression model that fit well was for diastolic blood pressure vs systolic blood pressure, grouped by cause of death
  • The best fit is for patients that have died from respiratory disease

Repo

Predicting death cause with logistic regression

  • The most important predictors for predicting if a patient died from prostate cancer (determined from ANOVA) were stage/grade index and prostatic acid phosphatase levels
  • 5-fold cross validation gave a model accuracy of 74.5%

Repo

Predicting cause of death with ANN

  • The ANN predicts on 10 different outcomes
  • The ANN was trained through 200 epochs, accuracy is shown in the plot

Repo

Clustering

Identifying clusters with PCA

  • A PCA analysis is used to look for groupings and patterns of the data based on all variables
  • PCA analysis is not well suited for this data, since a single PCA cannot explain a lot of the variance levels
  • PC #1 only explains 22.5% of the variance

Repo

Identifying clusters with PCA

  • No clear clusters could be identified
  • The best clusters are found when stratifying by status and if a person developed bone metastases

Repo

Conclusions

  • Prostatic acid (PA) phosphatase levels are higher in patients with metastases and that have died from prostate cancer
  • The risk of dying from prostate cancer increases with larger tumors
  • Serum hemoglobin levels are lower in older patients with bone metastases
  • When the cancer has metastasized the patients are less active and there is a much bigger risk of dying
  • High doses of estrogen have negative effects for older patients
  • Logistic regression can predict with 75% accuracy if a patient have died from prostate cancer, with the most important predictors being stage/grade index and PA phosphatase levels
  • An ANN was created with the aim of predicting the cause of death
  • The data has no clearly seperated clusters
